items.title: Mesophellia spp.
items.content_text: Three images. A truffle-like species which is unusual in that the spores form in a space around an infertile core. The core is believed to be high in nutrients which is the reward for the mammal that finds, eats and disperses the species. In other truffle-like species virtually all the inside of the fungus contains fertile spore producing material.

items.title: Hygrocybe pseudograminicolor
items.content_text: Several images. This species was believed to be associated with Myrtle Beech, Nothofagus cunninghamii, but now I have located it at two locations in the Wombat Forest plus there is a record to the north of Macedon. Like its near namesake, it could be a Gliophorus soon.

items.title: Hygrocybe graminicolor
items.content_text: Several images. This species starts off with a green cap that ages to brown. The current status of this name is not clear, Index Fungorum lists it as Gliophorus graminicolor whereas ALA still retains the older title, Hygrocybe graminicolor.

items.content_text:
This is Phlebia subceracea, previously known as Mycoacia subceracea, it is not listed in the database under either name so needs to be added please.
It is not always this orange looking, frequently having a more yellow appearance.

items.title: Callistosporium spp.
items.content_text: 3 images, this looks very similar to the last species (Tubaria rufofulva), but lacks the annulus and has white spores, The gill edge is also coloured. This is an as yet unnamed species of Callistosporium, recorded as Callistosporium 'maroon with yellow rhizomorphs' in Gates & Ratkowsky - A Field Guide to Tasmanian Fungi. Could Callistosporium spp be added to the database please.

items.title: Tubaria rufofulva
items.content_text: 3 Images, this is Tubaria rufofulva. Could the database be updated please. This species has an annulus (ring on stem) and brown spores which you can see in the first image.

items.title: Torrendiella eucalypti
items.content_text: This species now has a new name - Hymenotorrendiella eucalypti, could this be updated please, The tiny cups are around 1-1.75mm in diameter and they only occur on the leaves of the Blackwood, Acacia melanoxylon in wet forest. Like much of Australia's fungi, this species was named from collections sent overseas, in this instance M. J. Berkeley described it's habit as "on leaves of Eucalyptus", hence the naming error.

items.title: Psathyrella echinata
items.content_text: This image shows the full development of the species with tiny furry buttons on the far left through to collapsing and spent mushroom on the far right. Second images shows closer detail of the main group.

items.title: Fistulinella mollis
items.content_text: See cap in second image. A soft marshmallow-like bolete.

items.title: Orbilia spp.
items.content_text: These tiny translucent orange discs look very much like Orbilia cf xanthostigma as reported in the the Gates & Ratkowsky publication A Field Guide to Tasmanian Fungi. Best left as Orbilia sp. for now.

items.title: Cystolepiota spp.
items.content_text: An as yet unnamed species but reported in the Gates & Ratkowsky  publication A Field Guide to Tasmanian Fungi as Cystolepiota sp. 'small white'. The daggy bits hanging off the edge of the cap and the white gills are indicative of the species. Two images.

items.title: Mycena epipterygia
items.content_text: It seems that there is a group of yellow-stemmed Mycena species that are all covered under the name Mycena epipterygia Group until further research is completed.

items.title: Deconica horizontalis
items.content_text:
Three images, this is Deconica horizontalis, previously recorded as Melanotus hepatochrous in one field guide and as Psilocybe hepatochrous in another guide. It appears on ALA, could the database be updated please.
It is similar to the previous species but has purple/brown spores.

items.title: Cantharellus spp.
items.content_text: This much rarer species has also been described to me as Cantharellus concinnus but its form is so different that I struggle to think of it as being the same. Like the previous posting, the location is a general guide only. Two images.

items.title: Cantharellus concinnus
items.content_text: This species is listed as Cantharellus concinnus, could the database be updated please. The location as used here is a general guide only due to this being a prized edible species that I would rather see doing its work in the forest than sitting on a gourmand's dinner plate. Four images.

items.title: Neobarya agaricicola
items.content_text: This is Neobarya agaricicola that feeds on the older fruit bodies of other fungi such as Galerina species. It produces  tiny golden pear-shaped flasks that contain its spores. Could it be added to the database please.

items.title: Ascocoryne sarcoides
items.content_text: The smaller white capped clubs are the conidial (asexual) phase of this species and the larger purple discs are the spore producers

items.title: Torrendiella clelandii

items.title: Hydnellum auratile
items.content_text:
This is listed as Hydnellum auratile on the FNCV Fungi Group lists and appears under this name in Fuhrer, A Field Guide to Australian Fungi. Second image shows detail of the tan coloured spines.

The similar looking Phelledon niger is a darker charcoal or black on the cap and has grey spines.

items.title: Gliophorus chromolimoneus
items.content_text: This is Gliophorus chromolimoneus, formerly known as Hygrocybe chromolimonea. The bright yellow cap, stem and gills make this an easy one to identify. Could it be included in the database please.

items.title: Marasmius crinis-equi
items.content_text: This is Marasmius crinis-equi, the small dimple with the dark spot in the centre of the cap and the horse-hair stem (see second image) are clear indentifiers. Please add to database.

items.title: Coltriciella dependens
items.content_text: Not often seen unless you are in the habit of looking at the underside of sticks in the forest.

items.title: Hypoxylon howeanum
items.content_text:
This species is sometimes illustrated in Australia as H. fuscum, The red brick coloured balls are the sexual reproductive stage and the hairy looking star-like clusters nearby are the asexual anamorph stage. See second image for detail on the anamorph.

The tiny pale discs in the first image have not been identified.

items.title: Dermocybe canaria
items.content_text: 3 images - This species is now known as Cortinarius canarius, could the new name be added to the database please. Recent molecular work has returned all the Australian Dermocybe back to Cortinarius

items.content_text: 2 images. This species has been previously misidentified as R. gracilis which apparently does not occur in Australia.

items.title: Entoloma rodwayi
items.content_text: See other images, the blue staining on the base of the stipe, seen in the last image, is diagnostic for this species.

items.title: Auriscalpium spp.
items.content_text: I am told that this extremely rare species was recently formally named and is now known as Auriscalpium greyorum, after the original finders. It grows on one tree only near Blackwood.
